[
  {
    "text": "The LSOG product provides a continuous per‑pixel probability of occurrence, whereas the Hagan et al. (2026) LiDAR map is a discrete (binary or multi‑class) classification of LSOG presence.",
    "topic": "Data type"
  },
  {
    "text": "A direct overlay of a continuous probability surface with a discrete classification, without any harmonization step such as thresholding or probabilistic evaluation, is not an apples‑to‑apples comparison.",
    "topic": "Comparability definition"
  },
  {
    "text": "An apples‑to‑apples comparison requires either converting the probability map into a discrete classification using a threshold calibrated against FIA plot‑based prevalence, or evaluating the continuous map with metrics that accommodate probabilistic predictions from a design‑based standpoint.",
    "topic": "Required harmonization"
  },
  {
    "text": "The LSOG mapping framework is design‑based and anchored to FIA plots, while the Hagan et al. LiDAR classification is model‑based; an apples‑to‑apples comparison must reconcile these inference frameworks, for instance through post‑stratification or small‑area estimation.",
    "topic": "Inference framework"
  }
]
